title: Development of a Real-Time Fingering Detection System for Contrabass Using Musical Rules
title_en: Development of a Real-Time Fingering Detection System for Contrabass Using Musical Rules
abstract: 本研究はコントラバス演奏における運指（フィンガリング）をリアルタイムで自動検出する手法を提案している。提案する手法は楽曲に基づく音楽ルールとマーカ検出の確度を組み合わせて運指を推定し、マーカの確度が高い方を優先する判定や手の形の特性を考慮する規則によりフレット位置や指割り当てを推定することを目的としている。
abstract_en: This work proposes a method to automatically detect fingering for contrabass performance in real time. The proposed method combines musical-rule-based decision mechanisms with marker-detection confidence and hand-shape characteristics to infer fret positions and finger assignments by preferring higher-confidence markers.
positioning_summary: 本研究はコントラバスの演奏中に発生する運指の曖昧性と誤検出の問題に取り組む研究として位置づけられている。位置づけとして本研究は演奏支援や自動採譜など運指情報を必要とする応用に資するリアルタイムの運指検出技術の開発を目標としている。
positioning_summary_en: This research is positioned as addressing ambiguity and misdetection of fingering during contrabass performance. The positioning states that the research aims to develop a real-time fingering detection technology to support applications such as performance assistance and automatic transcription.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的はコントラバス演奏における各指の検出ずれやマーカ検出の不確かさを解消して運指推定の精度を向上させることである。目的として本研究は音楽的ルールを活用して複数指が同一フレットにある場合やフレットずれの問題を扱い，実時間での運指推定を実現することを目指している。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this research is to improve fingering estimation accuracy by resolving per-finger detection offsets and uncertainty in marker detection for contrabass performance. The purpose states that the research aims to apply musical rules to handle cases such as multiple fingers on the same fret and fret offsets and to realize real-time fingering estimation.
method_summary: 本研究は指先に付けたマーカの検出確度を基準にして高確度のマーカを運指として選択するルールベースのリアルタイム検出機構を実装した。方法として本研究は手の形の特性と楽曲に基づく音楽ルール（例: 親指や指番号の使用規則）を組み込み，マーカ確度やルール適用によりフレット位置と指番号（0,T,1,2,3,4）を推定する処理を行っている。
method_summary_en: This study implemented a rule-based real-time detection mechanism that selects fingering based on the detection confidence of markers attached to fingertips. The method incorporates hand-shape characteristics and musical rules (e.g., thumb and finger-number usage rules) and estimates fret positions and finger numbers (0, T, 1, 2, 3, 4) by applying marker confidence and rule-based selection.
evaluation_summary: 本研究は複数の楽曲を用いてルール適用時と未適用時を比較する事例比較とミス計測によって評価を行った。評価ではルール適用が誤検出を減少させることが示され，人差し指は安定して検出される一方で薬指は1〜2フレット上にずれる事例が観察され，評価指標は約4.0〜4.3や3.6といったスコアが報告された。
evaluation_summary_en: The study evaluated the system by comparing rule-applied and rule-not-applied conditions across multiple musical pieces using case comparisons and misdetection counts. The evaluation observed that rule application reduced misdetections, that the index finger was stably detected whereas the ring finger showed 1–2 fret upward offsets in some cases, and reported scores around 4.0–4.3 and 3.6.

Title: Development of a Real-Time Fingering Detection System for Contrabass Using Musical Rules
Authors: Mitsuteru Sawa, Tsutomu Terada, Masahiko Tsukamoto, Yoshinari Takegawa
Year: 2008
Abstract: This work proposes a method to automatically detect fingering for contrabass performance in real time. The proposed method combines musical-rule-based decision mechanisms with marker-detection confidence and hand-shape characteristics to infer fret positions and finger assignments by preferring higher-confidence markers.
Positioning Summary: This research is positioned as addressing ambiguity and misdetection of fingering during contrabass performance. The positioning states that the research aims to develop a real-time fingering detection technology to support applications such as performance assistance and automatic transcription.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this research is to improve fingering estimation accuracy by resolving per-finger detection offsets and uncertainty in marker detection for contrabass performance. The purpose states that the research aims to apply musical rules to handle cases such as multiple fingers on the same fret and fret offsets and to realize real-time fingering estimation.
Method Summary: This study implemented a rule-based real-time detection mechanism that selects fingering based on the detection confidence of markers attached to fingertips. The method incorporates hand-shape characteristics and musical rules (e.g., thumb and finger-number usage rules) and estimates fret positions and finger numbers (0, T, 1, 2, 3, 4) by applying marker confidence and rule-based selection.
Evaluation Summary: The study evaluated the system by comparing rule-applied and rule-not-applied conditions across multiple musical pieces using case comparisons and misdetection counts. The evaluation observed that rule application reduced misdetections, that the index finger was stably detected whereas the ring finger showed 1–2 fret upward offsets in some cases, and reported scores around 4.0–4.3 and 3.6.
